SIMPLE: flail
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flail
<hw>Flail</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>flagellum</ets>
whip, scourge, in LL., a threshing flail: cf. OF. <ets>flael</ets>,
<ets>flaiel</ets>, F. <ets>fl⟦eacute⟧au</ets>. See
<er>Flagellum</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An instrument for threshing
or beating grain from the ear by hand, consisting of a wooden staff or
handle, at the end of which a stouter and shorter pole or club, called a
swipe, is so hung as to swing freely.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His shadowy <qex>flail</qex> hath threshed the corn.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An ancient military weapon, like the common flail,
often having the striking part armed with rows of spikes, or
loaded.</def> <rj><au>Fairholt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No citizen thought himself safe unless he carried under his coat a
small <qex>flail</qex>, loaded with lead, to brain the Popish
assassins.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flaily</ent>⟦br⟧
